## Buyback with cap on the volume, floating notional and price cap

Finally, we add a price cap to the program and consider the following parameters:

- Maturity: $N_{\text {min }}=60$ days, $N_{\text {max }}=65$ days;
- Notional: $F_{\text {min }}=200 \mathrm{M} €, F_{\text {max }}=250 \mathrm{M} €$;
- Early exercise: $N_{e x}=40$ days;
- Bounds: $v_{\text {min }}=0, v_{\text {max }}=0.2 \frac{\tilde{V}}{S_{0} \Delta t}$;
- Price cap: $S_{\max }=1.2 S_{0}=12 €$.

We compare the different strategies and report the results in the table below.

![table_4](table_4)

Again, our six strategies clearly beat the benchmarks. We also see, as above, that increasing the complexity of the strategy by adding a dependence of the execution strategy on the $\frac{A}{S}$ ratio significantly enhances the average PnL.
